To multiply two numbers in base 8, we can perform the same steps as in decimal multiplication, but taking into account the base. 

\[
\begin{array}{r}
  44046_{8} \\
\times 21706_{8} \\
\hline
\end{array}
\]

\[
\begin{array}{r}
\phantom{00}44046_{8} \\
\underline{\times \phantom{000}21706_{8}} \\
\phantom{0}264276_{8} \quad \text{(Multiplying the units place)}\\
44046_{8} \quad \text{(Shifting the second number by one place to the left)}\\
\underline{308322_{8} \quad \text{(Multiplying the 8's place)}}\\
2642024_{8} \quad \text{(Adding the two results)}
\end{array}
\]

Therefore, \(44046_{8} * 21706_{8} = 2642024_{8}\)